{{other uses|T-square (disambiguation)}}
{{refimprove|date=September 2014}}
[[File:Drafting board with T Square.jpg|thumb|Drafting board with a T-square and triangle]]
A '''T-square''' is a technical [[plan (drawing)|drawing]] [[Measuring instrument|instrument]] used by [[technical drawing|draftsmen]] primarily as a guide for drawing horizontal lines on a [[drafting table]]. It may also guide a set square to draw vertical or diagonal lines.<ref name = "Drafting 1940">{{cite book | last = United States War Department | title = Topographic Drafting | publisher = U.S. Government Printing Office | date = 1940 | pages = 27–28 | url = http://books.google.com/books?id=3y-7iT046m8C&pg=PA27}}</ref> Its name comes from its resemblance to the letter T. T-squares come in varying sizes, common lengths being {{convert|18|inch}}, {{convert|24|inch}}, {{convert|30|inch}}, {{convert|36|inch}} and {{convert|42|inch}}.{{Citation needed|date=September 2010}}

T-squares are also used to measure and cut [[drywall]]. Drywall T-squares are typically made of [[aluminium]] and have a {{convert|48|inch|adj=on}} long [[tongue]].

Higher-end [[table saw]]s are often equipped with T-square [[fence (woodworking)|fence]]s. These table saw fences are attached to a rail only on the front side of the table unlike traditional fences which clamp to both the front and the rear of the table.

A T-square has two components - the long shaft called the "blade" and the short shaft called the "stock" or "head". The T-square usually has a [[transparency and translucency|transparent]] edge made of [[plastic]] which should be free of nicks and cracks in order to provide smooth, straight lines.

